{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507647"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:55:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:55:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2654"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2654"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0.03,0.24,0.04,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2654"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44015"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2654"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2654"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28996"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"581"},{"type":"tags","id":"2697"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3103"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3257"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3274"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10880"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19075"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44015"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man is reviewed in the outpatient clinic four months after a left superficial parotidectomy for a pleomorphic adenoma. The procedure was uncomplicated and he went home two days after the surgery. He now complains of sweating and flushing of the left side of his face when he eats spicy or sour foods. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Parasympathetic nerve injury","General hyperhidrosis","Gustatory hyperlacrimation","Salivary fistula","Parotid duct stenosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has a \u003Cstrong\u003Eparasympathetic nerve injury\u003C/strong\u003E. He has gustatory sweating, a condition otherwise known as Frey\u2019s syndrome. The cause of this problem is development of aberrant parasympathetic nerve supply to the skin and its appendages overlying the parotid bed following parotidectomy. These nerve fibres control sweat gland activity and there has been inappropriate regeneration of the fibres of the auriculotemporal branch of the temporal nerve. This late complication is that salivary gland stimulation (meals, thought or smell of food) results in sweating/flushing of the face. The abnormal regeneration of parasympathetic nerve fibres may occur from months to years after the procedure. Patients can manage this condition with topical application of deodorant to the affected skin. For more severe manifestations, botulinum toxin can provide effective symptom control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGeneral hyperhidrosis\u003C/strong\u003E can be classified as primary involving the axillary, palmoplantar or craniofacial regions, and is often idiopathic. Secondary hyperhidrosis involves excessive sweating due to pathologies involving endocrine, infectious, cardiovascular, toxicological, malignancy, and traumatic causes. Although craniofacial hyperhidrosis is often exacerbated by spicy food consumption, it will usually present with bilateral, constant sweating present for over 6 months, that ceases during sleep.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGustatory hyperlacrimination\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as crocodile tears or Bogorad\u2019s syndrome) presents with unilateral tearing when presented with a gustatory stimulus. It is believed to be due to aberrant regeneration of pre-ganglionic parasympathetic fibres within the facial nerve that supply the lacrimal, as well as mucosal, submaxillary, sublingual, and salivary glands. This condition is commonly associated with long term Bell\u2019s palsy, which this patient does not have, and would not explain the sweating.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESalivary fistulas\u003C/strong\u003E typically manifest in the immediate postoperative period or shortly thereafter, rather than four months after surgery. While delayed presentations of salivary fistulas are possible, they are less common, and symptoms usually occur within days to weeks following surgery. They typically present with leakage of saliva from the surgical site, leading to persistent wetness or moisture around the incision area. While sweating and flushing of the face can occur due to the presence of excess saliva, these symptoms are usually not specifically tied to eating and may persist beyond meal times. Also, the patient denies any pain or discomfort associated with the episodes of sweating and flushing, which are common features of salivary fistulas. Additionally, there is no mention of visible leakage of saliva or persistent wetness around the surgical site, which would be expected in the presence of a salivary fistula.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParotid duct stenosis \u003C/strong\u003Ecan lead to symptoms such as saliva retention, swelling of the parotid gland, and possibly pain or discomfort, but it is less likely to manifest specifically as sweating and flushing during meals without other associated symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A late complication of parotidectomy is Frey\u0027s syndrome, where development of aberrant parasympathetic nerve supply causes gustatory sweating."],"references":["Mantelakis A, Lafford G, Lee CW, et al. Frey\u2019s Syndrome: A Review of Aetiology and Treatment. Cureus 2021; 13"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28996"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2654"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28996","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28996"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-04T17:40:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-10T18:27:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2654"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44015"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null